  <chapter id="features">
      <title>Features</title>

    <sect1 id="starting-program">
      <title>Starting a Program</title> 

      <para>You can simply start any program by typing its name.</para>
    </sect1>

    <sect1 id="command-completion">
      <title>Command Completion</title> 

      <para>You often have not to enter the full name but only the
      first characters followed by the <keycap>tab</keycap>
      key. &mini-c; will try to complete the program name in the same
      way most UNIX shells do.</para>
    </sect1>

    <sect1 id="command-history">
      <title>Command History</title> 

      <para>The last commands can be recalled by pressing the
      <keycap>arrow-up</keycap> or <keycap>arrow-down</keycap>
      keys. This works like the command history in most UNIX
      shells.</para>

      <para>A command is not stored in the history when it is the same
      as the command before.  This way dupes are prevented.</para>
    </sect1>

    <sect1 id="macros">
      <title>Macros</title> 

      <para>&mini-c; has some predefined macros. For example if
      you enter "term:command" then "command" is executed in a
      terminal window. Or if you enter an URL then your web browser is
      used to view it.  Additionally you can define your own macros or
      change the predefined ones.</para>
    </sect1>

    <sect1 id="clock">
      <title>Clock</title> 

      <para>There is a built-in clock which can optionally show the
      date or can be completely disabled.</para>
    </sect1>

  </chapter>



